metadata.name: Linear Composition, Vol. 2 #1
metadata.description:
Inspired by old dot-matrix printers and in continuation of one of my previous series, "linear composition", this artwork explores linear and rectangular compositions combined with a very large matrix of small unique circular shapes . To see the artwork in detail, it is recommended to view it in high quality and zoom in. Various densities and more than 12 color palettes have been used.

-----------

- Add &density=2 to 12 to the live view URL to render the image at higher resolution.

- Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: XTreeZ #12
metadata.description:
Press 'S' key to save canvas as 800x1200 png
Press 'X' key to add one XTreez

Although XTreeZ trunk and branch growth are predictable, the addition of extra secondary branches and leaves create a striking resemblance to high altitude coniferous trees or bonsai. For this reason, XTreeZ are envisioned in millimeters. Each setting is random and may invoke an atmosphere almost entirely dependent on the suns placement and color.

made with p5js

metadata.name: Luminaries #33
metadata.description:
There is no light without dark.

Luminaries is a study in symmetry, contrast and flow, with a palette inspired by the twelve full moon names. Owning a Luminary enables you to request a signed print for an additional fee. 

You can learn more about features and prints at: https://www.phaust.art/luminary

Each Luminary is composed of moons in various phases. Their layout derived from a handful of geometries. They contrast with their surroundings: filled with glittering stars, inky strokes or solid colour. 

Backgrounds can split along lines of symmetry – with dark and light contrasting as strokes seamlessly flow across the two halves. 

Luminaries are alive. They’re in retrograde once a month, a day in which you’ll see yours in a new light.

------

Collection Size: 158. One for each of the confirmed moons in our solar system.

Palettes: 12 + 1. One for each of the full moons plus a rarer secret palette: Wolf, Snow, Worm, Pink, Flower, Strawberry, Buck, Sturgeon, Harvest, Hunter, Beaver, Cold, ????.

Retrograde: day of the month that your Luminary will change for one day only.

S: to save at high resolution. 

Prints: request from https://www.phaust.art/luminary

metadata.name: 7VV1N5 #67
metadata.description:
GO BIG OR GO HOME.

After a week of minimalism code, our hero, the handsome artist Daniel, decided he needed something involving maximalism to reset the balance. Finding pairs to put together is satisfying.

Images will take 6-9 seconds to display and refresh between window resizing.

Use the z key or single click/tap to switch to "zoom" mode, which zooms in and fills the viewport; use z & tap/click to cycle through views. Use x and double-click/tap to go back to square mode.

Note: It doesn't work on Internet Explorer, because Microsoft. iOS is faster than Android.

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

z, click, tap - Switch to & cycle "zoom" mode
x, double-click, double-tap - Switch back out of "zoom" mode.
h - Toggle high-res (slow)
s - Download and save image (takes a few seconds, longer for high-res)

metadata.name: Leaky Planetary #4
metadata.description:
Have you ever seen an Aurora?

Every day the phenomenon of the Aurora occurs and when its colorful light appears over the Arctic and Antarctic Circles, it is a signal that thousands of tons of oxygen are escaping from the earth's atmosphere.

It would take billions of years for the atmosphere to completely disappear in those tons. The beautiful aurora phenomenon that many people are expecting to see and enjoy is actually a stark reminder of how fragile our earth is.

Press ’s’ on the live mode after 'zoom-out' the live mode tab to save the high-quality screen capture.

n.b. The smaller the zoom percentage, the higher the image quality you will get.

Made using Hydra (https://hydra.ojack.xyz/)

linxirwengi - 2023
